  "prompt": "If a truck is hauling 1000 pounds of parakeets that are all sitting on their perch does it get 1000 pounds lighter if they all fly at the same time?",
  "response": "No, the truck does not get 1000 pounds lighter if the parakeets all fly at the same time inside it. The total weight of the system (truck plus parakeets) remains the same. \n\nWhen the parakeets are flying, they are still within the truck and exert force downward on the air by flapping their wings. This action creates an equal and opposite reaction force (due to Newton's third law) that is transferred to the truck via the air pressure. The truck still supports the weight of the parakeets through this interaction, and thus the total weight of the system does not change. The weight is effectively transferred from the parakeets to the air inside the truck, and from the air to the truck's structure.",
